l interpretations, the imaginary schemes elaborated for giving accounts of the journeys to the other world, for communicating with the dead, and finally the historical archetypes of this kind of religious manifestation—trance prophecy, divination, and shamanism.Recognized historians and ethnologists analyze the relationship, coexistence and conflicts of popular belief systems, Judeo-Christian mythology and demonology in medieval and modern Europe. The essays address links between rites and beliefs, folklore and literature; the legacy of various pre-Christian mythologies; the syncretic forms of ancient, medieval and modern belief- and rite-systems; "pure" examples from religious-ethnological research outside Europe to elucidate European problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDemonologyxCongressesxHistoryxEurope. 0aDemonologyzEuropexHistoryvCongresses. 0aFolklorexCongressesxHistoryxEuropexEurope. 0aFolklorezEuropexHistoryvCongresses. 0aWitchcraftxCongressesxHistoryxEurope. 0aWitchcraftzEuropexHistoryvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnthropology, Demonology, Folklore, Religion, Witchcraft.1 aBehringer, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchholz, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaciola, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDapit, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagen, Rune Blix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoudard, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaniczay, Gábor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaniczay, Gábor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMikolajczyk, Re